      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Italian-Origin Words: Music's Gift to Scrabble</h2>
      <p>Western classical music adopted Italian as its lingua franca centuries ago. The result? Dozens of Italian words entered English dictionaries without translation. For Scrabble players, this is a treasure trove — these words use vowel-heavy letter combinations that complement consonant-heavy racks.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎵 Italian Terms (Valid)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">FORTE (8), TEMPO (9), RONDO (6), FUGUE (9), OCTAVE (11) — vowel-rich, great for balancing consonant-heavy racks</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎼 Dance Forms (Valid)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">WALTZ (17), POLKA (11) — Germanic and Czech origins with high-value consonants W, K, Z</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>FUGUE is particularly elegant — it uses F (4 pts) plus four common letters for 9 points. The double-U makes it useful when you're stuck with multiple U tiles. TEMPO and FORTE both score well with their F and M/P combinations. RONDO uses common letters but deploys them efficiently at 6 points for 5 letters. These Italian words rarely get challenged because even non-musicians recognize them.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">WALTZ is the <span class="text-white font-medium">ultimate music word</span> for Scrabble: Z (10 pts) + W (4 pts) = 14 points from just two tiles, with A, L, T filling common rack letters. On a Triple Word Score, that's 51 points from 5 letters.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">High-Scoring Music Plays</h2>
      <p>The best musical words for scoring combine high-value tiles (Z, H, W, K, Y, F) with common letters. WALTZ dominates with Z+W, while HYMN packs 12 points into just 4 letters using H+Y+M — an incredibly efficient ratio of 3 points per tile.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">WALTZ</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">17 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">HYMN</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">CHIME</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">CHORD</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">11 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">POLKA</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">11 pts</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <p>HYMN is remarkable because it scores 12 points from only 4 letters — that's 3.0 points per tile, matching premium words like QI. It also has no vowels, making it perfect when your rack is consonant-heavy. CHORD and CHIME both leverage the C+H combination (7 pts from 2 tiles) that appears in many English words. POLKA uses K (5 pts) alongside very common letters for an easy 11-point play.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Music Words by Category</h2>
      <p>Musical vocabulary spans instruments, theory, forms, and performance. Each category offers different strategic advantages depending on your rack and the board state.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎸 Instruments</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">CELLO (7), OBOE (6), GONG (6) — shorter words for tight board positions</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">📐 Music Theory</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">CHORD (11), OCTAVE (11), CLEF (9), LYRIC (10) — mid-range scorers with common letters</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">💃 Dance Forms</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">WALTZ (17), POLKA (11) — highest scorers due to Z and K tiles</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎤 Performance</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">FORTE (8), TEMPO (9), STRUM (7), THRUM (10) — action words that extend well (-ED, -ING)</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy Tips for Musical Terms</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">WALTZ is your Z-word safety net:</span> When you draw Z but can't play QUIZ or PIZZA, WALTZ uses common letters (W, A, L, T) that are almost always available. It's one of the most reliable Z-word plays in the game.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">HYMN for vowel-free plays:</span> With zero vowels, HYMN is perfect when your rack is all consonants. At 12 points in 4 letters, it's one of the highest-scoring vowel-free words. HYMNS adds an S for 13 points.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">FUGUE for double-U racks:</span> Drawing two U tiles is usually painful. FUGUE uses both U tiles productively for 9 points. It's one of very few common words with two U's that aren't too long to play.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Extend with -ED and -S:</span> WALTZED (23 pts), CHIMED (14 pts), STRUMMED, THRUMMED. Dance words extend naturally: POLKAS, WALTZES. These extensions can hit bingo territory at 7+ letters.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">CHORD for CH- hooks:</span> If someone plays a word ending in C, you can hook CHORD starting from that C position. The CH combination is powerful at 7 points for 2 tiles, and CHORD uses only common remaining letters (O, R, D).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
